==[[Rugby league]]== {{main|2012 in rugby league}} *[[2012 Challenge Cup]] - [[Warrington Wolves]] win, defeating [[Leeds Rhinos]] in the final. *[[2012 European Cup (rugby league)|2012 European Cup]] - the [[England national rugby league team|England Knights]] won. *[[2012 New South Wales Cup season]] *[[2012 New Zealand rugby league season]] *[[2012 National League Cup]] *[[2012 RFL Championship]] *[[2012 State of Origin series]] – {{leagueicon|Queensland|16}} [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]] defeats {{leagueicon|NSW|16}} [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] 2–1 in the best-of-3 series, extending the northerners' all-time record for consecutive State of Origin wins to seven. *[[Super League XVII]] – {{leagueicon|Leeds|16}} [[Leeds Rhinos]] defeat {{leagueicon|Warrington|16}} [[Warrington Wolves]] 26–18 in the [[2012 Super League Grand Final|Grand Final]] to claim their second consecutive championship and fifth in the last six seasons. *[[2012 USARL season]] *[[Leeds Rhinos]] win the [[2012 World Club Challenge]]
==[[Rugby union]]== {{main|2012 in rugby union}} *February 4 – 17 March: [[2012 Six Nations Championship|Six Nations Championship]] ** {{ru|WAL}} win the championship for the 25th time, also claiming their 11th [[Grand Slam (rugby union)|Grand Slam]] and 20th [[Triple Crown (rugby union)|Triple Crown]]. * May 18: [[2011–12 European Challenge Cup#Final|Amlin Challenge Cup Final]] at [[Twickenham Stoop|The Stoop]], London: ** {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Biarritz Olympique|Biarritz]] defeat {{flagicon|FRA}} [[RC Toulonnais|Toulon]] 21–18 to claim their first Challenge Cup title and first European trophy. * May 19: [[2012 Heineken Cup Final|Heineken Cup Final]] at [[Twickenham Stadium|Twickenham]], London ** {{flagicon|IRE|rugby union}} [[Leinster Rugby|Leinster]] crush {{flagicon|IRE|rugby union}} [[Ulster Rugby|Ulster]] 42–14 for their third Heineken Cup, becoming only the second club to successfully defend a Heineken Cup title and the first ever to win the Cup three times in four years. *[[2011–12 IRB Sevens World Series|IRB Sevens World Series]]: **{{Gold1}} '''{{ru7|NZL}}''', {{Silver2}} {{ru7|FJI}} and {{Bronze3}} {{ru7|ENG}}. New Zealand claim their second consecutive series crown and tenth overall. * June 4–22: [[2012 IRB Junior World Championship]] in [[Cape Town]] and [[Stellenbosch]], South Africa **{{Gold1}} '''{{ruu|20|ZAF}}''', {{Silver2}} {{ruu|20|NZL}} and {{Bronze3}} {{ruu|20|WAL}}. This was the first title for South Africa. It was also the first time in the competition's five-year history in which New Zealand did not claim the title. * June 16–30: [[2012 IRB Junior World Rugby Trophy]] in [[Salt Lake City]], United States **{{Gold1}} '''{{ruu|20|USA}}''', {{Silver2}} {{ruu|20|JPN}} and {{Bronze3}} {{ruu|20|TGA}}. This was the first title for the USA, which will be promoted to the [[2013 IRB Junior World Championship|2013 Junior World Championship]] at the expense of {{ruu|20|ITA}}. * August 4: [[2012 Super Rugby season|Super Rugby]] [[2012 Super Rugby Final|Final]] at [[Waikato Stadium]], [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]: ** The {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] crush the {{flagicon|ZAF}} [[Sharks (rugby union)|Sharks]] 37–6 to claim their first-ever title. * August 18 – October 6: [[2012 Rugby Championship|The Rugby Championship]] ** {{ru|NZL}} win the title with a clean sweep in the first season of the newly renamed competition, now including [[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina]]. Including the competition's previous history as the [[The Rugby Championship|Tri Nations]], this is the All Blacks' 11th series win.
;Domestic competitions * {{flagicon|ENG}} [[2011–12 English Premiership (rugby union)|English Premiership]] Final, May 26 at Twickenham: ** [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]] defeat [[Leicester Tigers]] 30–23 to claim their first Premiership title. Quins had also finished atop the league table. * [[2011–12 RFU Championship|RFU Championship]] Final, May 23 and May 30: ** [[London Welsh RFC|London Welsh]] defeat [[Cornish Pirates]] 66–41 on aggregate to claim the title. London Welsh were initially denied a place in the Premiership due largely to stadium issues, but successfully appealed the denial, placing them in the Premiership for 2012–13 at the expense of bottom finisher [[Newcastle Falcons]]. * {{flagicon|FRA}} [[2011–12 Top 14 season|Top 14]] Final, June 9 at [[Stade de France]], [[Saint-Denis, Seine-Saint-Denis|Saint-Denis]]: ** [[Stade Toulousain|Toulouse]] defeat [[RC Toulonnais|Toulon]] 18–12 and lift the [[Bouclier de Brennus]] for the 19th time. * [[2011–12 Rugby Pro D2 season|Rugby Pro D2]] — [[FC Grenoble|Grenoble]] automatically promoted to Top 14 as champion. [[Stade Montois|Mont-de-Marsan]] defeat [[Section Paloise|Pau]] 29–20 in the playoff final to claim the second promotion place. These teams replace [[Club athlétique Brive Corrèze Limousin|Brive]] and [[Lyon OU|Lyon]], which finished on the bottom of the Top 14 table. * {{flagicon|IRE|rugby union}} {{flagicon|ITA}} {{flagicon|SCO}} {{flagicon|WAL}} [[2011–12 Pro 12|Pro12]] Final, May 27 at [[RDS Arena]], [[Dublin]]: ** {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ospreys (rugby union)|Ospreys]] defeat {{flagicon|IRE|rugby union}} [[Leinster Rugby|Leinster]] 31–30 to claim their fourth [[Pro14|Celtic League/Pro12]] title. * {{flagicon|ENG}} {{flagicon|WAL}} [[2011–12 LV Cup|LV Cup]] (Anglo-Welsh Cup) – [[Leicester Tigers]] * {{flagicon|NZL}} [[2012 ITM Cup|ITM Cup]] ** Premiership Final, October 27 at [[Rugby League Park]], [[Christchurch]]: [[Canterbury representative rugby union team|Canterbury]] defeat [[Auckland representative rugby union team|Auckland]] 31–18 for their fifth consecutive provincial title. ** Championship Final, October 26 at [[Growers Stadium|ECOLight Stadium]], [[Pukekohe]]: [[Counties Manukau Rugby Union|Counties Manukau]] defeat [[Otago Rugby Football Union|Otago]] 41–16 to claim their first title at any level of provincial rugby in 32 years. The Steelers are promoted to the 2013 ITM Premiership, replacing bottom-placed [[Hawke's Bay Rugby Union|Hawke's Bay]]. * {{flagicon|ZAF}} [[2012 Currie Cup Premier Division|Currie Cup]] Final, October 27 at [[Kings Park Stadium|Mr Price Kings Park]], [[Durban]]: ** [[Western Province (rugby team)|Western Province]] defeat {{Rut Sharks (Currie Cup)}} 25–18 to claim their first Currie Cup title since 2001.
