{{Infobox NRHP | name = Montana State Fairgrounds Racetrack | nrhp_type = nrhp | image = | alt = | caption = | locmapin = USA Montana | map_alt = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|46|37|17|N|112|03|22|W|display=inline,title}} | location = 98 W. Custer Avenue, [[Helena, Montana]], U.S. | built = 1870 | architect = | architecture = | added = December 20, 2006 | designated_nrhp_type = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | refnum = 06001136<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | mpsub = }}
The '''Montana State Fairgrounds Racetrack''', also known as the '''Lewis and Clark County Fairgrounds Racetrack''' and as '''Helena Downs''', is a historic [[horse racing]] [[Race track|track]] located on the outskirts of [[Helena, Montana]], in the United States. Constructed in 1870, the track was part of the Montana State Fairgrounds, now the Lewis and Clark County Fairgrounds. The racetrack was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on December 20, 2006. Portions of the track were demolished from 2006 to 2008 due to new construction on the fairgrounds.
==Horse racing in Montana== [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] first brought horses to the northern [[Great Plains]] in the early to mid 1700s,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Haines|first=Francis|title=Where Did the Plains Indians Get Their Horses?|journal=American Anthropologist|date=January 1938|volume=40|issue=1|pages=112–117|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/store/10.1525/aa.1938.40.1.02a00110/asset/aa.1938.40.1.02a00110.pdf;jsessionid=7008E7BBD5A66ED3364307082955A2AC.f03t02?v=1&t=iat0wnap&s=5757a062a419446c1bd9957cbbdc6a4ba34c9e77|accessdate=May 19, 2015|doi=10.1525/aa.1938.40.1.02a00110}}</ref> and horse racing among Native Americans in what later became Montana was common.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gustafson|first=Sid|title=In Search of Montana Horse Racing|work=Big Sky Journal|date=May 2009|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=https://bigskyjournal.com/Features/Story/in-search-of-montana-horse-racing|postscript=none}}; {{cite book|last1=Thompson|first1=Francis M.|last2=Owens|first2=Kenneth N.|title=A Tenderfoot in Montana: Reminiscences of the Gold Rush, the Vigilantes, and the Birth of Montana Territory|location=Helena, Mont.|publisher=Montana Historical Society Press|date=2004|isbn=9780972152228|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lxge9bv1Z-wC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=134-135|postscript=none}}; {{cite book|last1=Aarstad|first1=Rich|last2=Arguimbau|first2=Ellen|last3=Baumler|first3=Ellen|last4=Porsild|first4=Charlene L.|last5=Shovers|first5=Brian|title=Montana Place Names From Alzada to Zortman|location=Helena, Mont.|publisher=Montana Historical Society Press|date=2009|isbn=9780975919613|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=08rAI9NEbcYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=218}}</ref> Horse racing also became popular among white settlers in the area, particularly miners.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pace|first=Dick|title=Golden Gulch: The Story of Montana's Fabulous Alder Gulch|location=Virginia City, Mont.|publisher=Virginia City Trading Co.|date=1970|page=56|postscript=none}}; {{cite book|last=Baumler|first=Ellen|title=Montana Moments: History On The Go|location=Helena, Mont.|publisher=Montana Historical Society Press|date=2010|isbn=9780975919682|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uZ2DAxACpdoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=157}}</ref>
Semi-formal local horse [[flat racing]] meets first occurred in Montana in [[Deer Lodge, Montana|Deer Lodge]], Helena, and [[Virginia City, Montana|Virginia City]] in the 1860s. Helena's first permanent horse racing track was Madam Coady's Two-Mile House,{{Efn|The exact location of Madam Coady's, and the racetrack, is not known.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=18 fn2}}<ref name=asshewas />}} a {{convert|1|mi|km}} track located a few miles from Helena. The first Montana Territorial Fair was held at the site 1868, and included Montana's first regionally-organized horse flat race. [[Harness racing]] was added at the second Territorial Fair in 1869.<ref name=baumler>{{cite news|last=Baumler|first=Ellen|title=Montana's Horse-Racing History Runs Deep|work=The Independent Record|date=April 16, 2006|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=http://helenair.com/lifestyles/montana-s-horse-racing-history-runs-deep/article_c38772f9-f0b5-5fa4-8561-98fc11a535e5.html}}</ref>
==The Montana State Fairgrounds track== ===Construction of the track=== In August 1870,<ref name=baumler /> a group of Helena businessmen and civic leaders organized a new association, the Montana Agricultural Mineral and Mechanical Association, to host a new regional fair.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=3}} Among the trustees of the new organization were such prominent Montanans as Daniel A. G. Floweree, Cornelius Hedges, Anton M. Holter, and [[Conrad Kohrs]]. The group purchased property outside Helena (at the current location of the Montana State Fairgrounds), and construction of the racetrack began immediately. The {{convert|1|mi|km}} track was built according to the rules of the [[American Horse Congress]] and the California State Agricultural Society, had a {{convert|0.25|mi|km|adj=on}} home stretch, and was wide enough to accommodate eight [[Sulky|sulkies]].<ref name=baumler /> It is unclear if the track was a regular oval or if it had slightly distorted third and fourth turns which gave it an irregular oblong shape.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=18-19, fn 18}}{{Efn|All existing map and photographic evidence indicates the home stretch, as constructed in 1870, remained in place as of 2003.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=18-19, fn 18}}}} At the time of its construction, it was the only regulation {{convert|1|mi|km}} track in the territory.<ref name=baumler />
Several other buildings were erected about the same time as the track was constructed. Grandstands were constructed probably at the same as the track,{{Efn|The date of construction is unclear, but 1870 is the likeliest date. They were definitely in place no later than 1887.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=39}}}} beginning near the starting line and extending eastward.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=39}} A "[[paddock]]" was built to the east of the grandstand, and around the first turn were three [[stable]]s.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=52-53}}{{Efn|The date of construction for the stables is unclear. They were definitely in place by 1887.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=52}} The nature of the "paddock" is unclear. The term denotes an enclosed by unroofed space for the temporary holding of animals, but there is some evidence that the "paddock" was a roofed building even in its earliest days. There is strong evidence that the "paddock" was roofed (and thus more like a stable or barn) by 1892, and probably rebuilt as a stable or barn in 1903 or 1904.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=15, 52-53}}}}
===Early history of the track=== Races were held throughout the summer (not just at fair-time).{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=5}} They attracted horses from as far away as [[Salt Lake City]], and even included some high-quality [[Kentucky]] [[thoroughbred]]s. By 1884, horse racing tracks had been built in [[Bozeman, Montana|Bozeman]] and [[Butte, Montana|Butte]], and a "Montana Circuit" for horse racing had evolved. Races at Montana Circuit tracks became more exclusive, and applicant horses had to be vetted by a nomination committee before being allowed to race.<ref name=baumler /> The Montana Circuit eventually expanded to 15 regulation tracks.<ref name=tyron>{{cite news|last=Tryon|first=Phyllis|title=Horse Racing Task Force gets financial support from industry|work=The Racing Journal|date=August 10, 2006|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=http://www.theracingjournal.com/news/article.php?article_id=751}}</ref> On either side of the finish line were judging stands. These are two-storied structures which gave judging officials a clear view of the finish line so that they might declare which horses won and placed in the race. Initially, these were merely covered platforms, but they were replaced several times over the years with more elaborate, permanent structures with walls, windows, and amenities.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=44}}
Montana became a [[U.S. state]] in 1889,<ref name=baumler /> and the fair was renamed the Montana State Fair in 1891 after being sold to a new group of investors.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=5}} Helena horse racing continued to gain in prestige, with owners in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], and [[Spokane, Washington]], sending entries. The track was rebuilt that year.<ref name=baumler />{{Efn|If the 1870 track were oblong, it is most likely it was corrected to a true oval at this time.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=18-19, fn 18}}}} A [[Montana Central Railway]] [[Branch line|spur]] reached the fairgrounds that same year, and local undocumented tradition claimed that several [[railroad car]]s of earth from Kentucky were laid on the track.<ref name=baumler />
The [[Panic of 1893]] created significant economic disruption in Montana, and the Montana State Fair shut down after the 1895 event. The fairgrounds were mortgaged, and the issuers of the loan foreclosed.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=5}}
===Period of state ownership=== Helena residents raised money in 1903 to buy the fairgrounds, which were donated to the state.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=5}} By this time, the track had so deteriorated that large amounts of soil had to be trucked in to restore the turns.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=57}} The state of Montana authorized a subsidized Montana State Fair in 1903, and in 1904 [[relay race]]s were added.<ref name=baumler /> About this time, a two-story raised platform was erected just outside the first turn. This platform was used by racing officials to direct animals and riders before and after races.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=52}} In 1904, the three stables were moved from the first turn to outside the far stretch and rebuilt as [[speed barn]]s. A fourth speed barn and three more stables were built at some point thereafter.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=50, 53}}{{Efn|There is some evidence that indicates the three new stables were built in 1904.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=51}}}} Two small [[cottage]]s were erected about this time as well. One was against the north fence between the speed barns and stables, and another was at the end of a long shed built east of the speed barns. The cottage attached to the shed was used by the racetrack veterinarian.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=51}}
Significant changes to the viewing area were made after 1904. Three sets of [[bleachers]] were erected at the racetrack between 1903 and 1914. The first (the "long bleachers") was erected about {{convert|700|ft|m}} west of the grandstands, probably in 1904. The second set was erected between 1904 and 1913 to the west of the grandstand, and the third (the "small bleachers") to the west of the long bleachers, probably in 1914.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=32}} The old grandstands were demolished in 1906, and replaced with larger ones. Roughly {{convert|260|ft|m}} long and {{convert|60|ft|m}} wide, they cost $20,000 (${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|20000|1906}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) and were capable of seating 5,000 people.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=39}} Beneath the grandstands were a small jockey's dressing room (eastern end), a [[restaurant]], and a room with betting windows.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=40}}
The horse racing at the Montana State Fair began to decline after the [[Montana Legislature]] banned [[gambling|betting]] on horse races in 1914. The fair's financial situation deteriorated when the state legislature significantly cut the subsidy in 1915, and a worsening decade-long [[drought]] led to fewer paying exhibitors.<ref name=baumler /> A {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} dirt automobile racing track was built in the horse racing track's infield in 1916, nestled against the first turn.<ref name=asshewas>{{cite web|title=The Fairgrounds: Home of the Montana Territorial and State Fairs 1870-1932|website=Helena As She Was|date=March 11, 2017|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=http://www.helenahistory.org/the_fairgrounds.htm}}</ref> Although horse racing remained popular at the fairgrounds,<ref name=baumler /> economic difficulties led to the fair's cancellation in 1926. Organizers managed to host only small fairs 1927 to 1932.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=7}}
The ban on gambling was lifted in 1930. That year, more than 350 high-quality racehorses from the U.S., [[Canada]], and [[Mexico]] raced at Helena, and [[parimutuel betting]] (assisted by an [[Tote board|automatic totaliser]]) first occurred.<ref name=baumler /> The "paddock" was abandoned the same year, and a true, open-air paddock was built next to it.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=53}}
===Closure and reopening=== The last Montana State Fair was held in Helena in 1932.<ref name=baumler /> The [[1935 Helena earthquake]] and several fires in the 1930s and 1940s destroyed several unspecified structures associated with the horse racing track.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=8}} In the fall of 1937, the three north stables and veterinarian's cottage burned down. Horse racing ended during this time, and the track was abandoned except for the small section in front of the grandstand (used as part of the automobile race track).{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=9}}
The largest of the four north barns was relocated to nearby Green Meadow Ranch about 1938.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|pages=20, 51}} The remaining three north barns either burned down or were demolished by 1951.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=51}} Both finish-line judging stands were removed by then as well.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=44}}
In mid-1953, the Capital City Racing Association constructed a {{convert|0.25|mi|km}} oval [[Stock car racing|stock car]] racing track inside the 1916 automobile track. It remained in until 1956.<ref name=asshewas>{{cite web|title=The Fairgrounds: Home of the Montana Territorial and State Fairs 1870-1932|website=Helena As She Was|date=March 11, 2017|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=http://www.helenahistory.org/the_fairgrounds.htm}}</ref>
Horse racing returned to the horse track in 1961 after organizers hosted the first [[Last Chance Stampede]] at the old fairgrounds.<ref name=baumler /> Some newspapers began referring to the horse track as "Helena Downs" at this time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Early|first=Dave|title=Horsemen Not Happy With Racing Secretary|work=The Independent Record|date=July 7, 1970|page=7|accessdate=May 15, 2017|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/35806018/}}</ref> Horse racing lasted until 1998,<ref name=tyron /> and a year later the state turned the fairgrounds over to Lewis and Clark County.<ref name=klinecleared>{{cite news|last=Kline|first=Larry|title=County cleared in lawsuit|work=The Independent Record|date=March 19, 2008|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=http://helenair.com/news/local/county-cleared-in-lawsuit/article_70ebbec0-bc2d-5e57-a700-747b1a1c2441.html}}</ref>
===County ownership and changes to the track=== The grandstands were demolished in 2000.<ref name=asshewas /> They had fallen into a decrepit state, and preservationists vigorously asked for them to be preserved. But the cost was too great, and the state declined to assume the cost.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=10}} New modern, metal bleachers were erected in their place, and in the infield just west of the first turn. The new grandstands, designed to accommodate [[rodeo]] activities in the infield, occupied about one-eighth of the horse racing track surface.<ref name=asshewas /> Both the second turn, home stretch, and backstretch were bulldozed to accommodate rodeo activities.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=14}}
The public discussion over the grandstands led the Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Office to conduct a historic assessment of the Montana State Fairgrounds in 2003.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=1}}
In 2005, the Lewis and Clark County Fair Board began consideration of a plan to reconfigured the old Montana State Fairgrounds for reuse.<ref name=support /> The plans called for a new grandstand and a large new exhibition building in the horse track infield, and demolition of the home stretch.<ref name=klinewhoa>{{cite news|last=Kline|first=Larry|title=Whoa there: Preservation group seeks halt to fairgrounds work|work=The Independent Record|date=August 31, 2006|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=http://helenair.com/news/local/whoa-there-preservation-group-seeks-halt-to-fairgrounds-work/article_9aa392ec-38a0-56ac-b13d-9e26848074c0.html}}</ref> Although there was support for the return of horse racing and restoration of the track, the fair board declined to amend the plan to accommodate it.<ref name=support>{{cite news|title=Horsemen's support needed in response to draft plan for Helena fairgrounds|work=The Racing Journal|date=May 6, 2005|accessdate=May 14, 2017|url=http://www.theracingjournal.com/news/article.php?article_id=250}}</ref> When the county began building an access road across the horse racing track in the fall of 2005 in preparation for construction, an organization named Save the Track Foundation unsuccessfully sued to have the road stopped.<ref name=klinewhoa />
In November 2006, Lewis and Clark County voters approved a $5.7 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|5700000|2006|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) tax levy to implement the changes proposed by the fair board.<ref name=klinewhoa />
Despite the partial blockage and demolition of the track, the horse racing track (but not any associated buildings) was added to the National Register of Historic Places in December 2006.<ref name=nris />
In 2006, the Save the Track Foundation filed several lawsuits to enjoin Lewis and Clark County from implementing its reconfiguration of the fairgrounds. The group claimed that the fair board had misled voters by failing to disclose that the horse racing track would be partially demolished and the infield used for construction. County officials said the reconfiguration plan saved most of the track for horse racing and preservation purposes, and that a lengthy planning process determined that partial demolition and use of the infield was the best use of the land given current and future needs.<ref name=klinewhoa /> A [[Montana District Courts|Montana District Court]] judge declined to issue a temporary injunction halting the plan, and in March 2008 issued a formal ruling in favor of the county. The ruling allowed final construction on the new {{convert|60000|sqft|m2}} exhibition building to go forward.<ref name=klinecleared />
==About the track== The Montana State Fairgrounds Racetrack is located in the center of the {{convert|160|acre|m2|adj=on}} fairgrounds.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=3}}
Grandstands, three sets of bleachers, an enclosed "paddock", two judging platforms, and three stables were built during the track's early history on the home stretch and first turn. Speed barns, three stables, and two cottages were built adjacent to the back stretch in the first two or three decades of the 20th century. No historic structures associated with the track's history remained as of 2006.{{sfn|Helena/Lewis and Clark County Historic Preservation Commission|2003|page=15}}
The Montana State Fairgrounds Racetrack was one of only three {{convert|1|mi|km|adj=on}} tracks west of the [[Mississippi River]] in 2005.<ref name=tyron /> It was reported to be the oldest of these {{convert|1|mi|km|adj=on}} tracks in 2006,<ref name=baumler /> as well as the oldest extant horse racing track in Montana, and the only racing track built in Montana's territorial period to survive into the 21st century.<ref name=baumler /> According to the ''[[American Racing Manual]]'', it was the second oldest horse racing track of its kind in the nation.<ref name=klinewhoa />
